1 (2) Utilizing naloxone hydrochloride in [a dosage of 4 milligrams; and]
2 the lowest dosage effective to restore breathing;
3 (c) Procedures for the distribution and administration of opioid antagonists,
4 including, without limitation, ensuring ease of access to opioid antagonists [.] ;
5 and
6 (d) Provisions ensuring that a student will not be subject to disciplinary
7 action by the institution for obtaining an opioid antagonist.
8 2. Each institution within the System may tailor the emergency response
9 plan described in subsection 1 to meet the needs and capacity of the institution
10 for implementing the plan. In tailoring an emergency response plan, an
11 institution may determine:
12 (a) Whether training related to the plan will be provided in person or
13 virtually and synchronously or asynchronously;
14 (b) The locations at the institution where opioid antagonists will be
15 accessible; and
16 (c) The manner in which opioid antagonists will be distributed at the
17 institution.
18 3. An emergency response plan described in subsection 1 may not require a
19 person to complete any training in order to obtain or administer an opioid
20 antagonist.
21 4. The Board of Regents may adopt a model emergency response plan that
22 meets the requirements of this section to assist institutions in developing their
23 emergency response plans pursuant to subsection 1. The Board of Regents may
24 not require an institution to utilize the model emergency response plan.
25 5. As used in this section:
26 (a) “Opioid antagonist” has the meaning ascribed to it in NRS 453C.040.
27 (b) “Opioid-related drug overdose” has the meaning ascribed to it in NRS
28 453C.050.
29 Sec. 2. This act becomes effective upon passage and approval.

